<center></center>
 Level 540 is the 541st [[Level List|broken machine]] of the Reality Factory.
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="8">| Description |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''Level 540 also known as "Monochrome Metropolis", is an infinite industrial cityscape resembling urban environments from the early 1900s. The level consists of densely packed buildings connected by wide streets paved with worn stone tiles. These streets are lined with scattered street lamps, which provide dim but consistent lighting throughout the environment. Large factory complexes, warehouses, and residential-style buildings dominate the landscape, giving the level a heavily industrialized appearance.'''

{{Blurimage|file=Captura de tela 2026-02-18 181700.png|caption=Level 540's Factories}}

'''All of Level 540 is enveloped in a strict black-and-white color scheme, affecting the environment, objects, and even wanderers themselves. This phenomenon is not merely a visual effect. Wanderers who enter the level will gradually lose all color, along with any belongings they carry. Upon exiting Level 540, both the wanderer and their items will remain monochromatic for a period of time, slowly regaining their original color over the course of approximately 3 hours to 2 weeks. The duration of this effect depends on how long the wanderer remained within the level. However, this restoration process does not apply to objects or entities that originate from Level 540, nor to Backborn individuals born within the level.'''

'''The terrain in Level 540 is primarily flat, with only minor fluctuations in elevation. In certain unstable regions, such as the so-called "Warped Zone," the ground may become uneven or distorted. These areas are often associated with structural irregularities and unusual spatial behavior.'''

'''Level 540 also features a day and night cycle similar to that of [[The Frontrooms]], although it is not entirely consistent. The timing and duration of day and night may vary slightly, and the transition between them can sometimes feel unnatural or delayed. During nighttime, the city becomes significantly darker, with only the street lamps and occasional building lights providing illumination.'''

'''Most buildings within Level 540 follow standard Euclidean geometry. However, some structures are affected by [[Phenomenon 14]], resulting in non-Euclidean properties such as impossible interiors, distorted angles, or shifting layouts. The likelihood of encountering these non-Euclidean structures increases the farther one travels from the central areas of the city, suggesting that the level becomes more unstable at greater distances.'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="8">| Locations |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

== '''Industrial Zone''' ==
'''The Industrial Zone is the most common and widespread area of Level 540.'''

{{Blurimage|file=Factory interior in Level 540.jpeg|caption=Inside one of the Industrial Zone's factories in Level 540}}

'''This zone is dominated by large factory complexes and industrial buildings that closely resemble those from the early 20th century. The architecture primarily consists of brick, steel frameworks, and reinforced concrete, with tall smokestacks and large windows being common features. The interiors of these factories are often filled with various forms of machinery, including conveyor systems, mechanical presses, boilers, and other industrial equipment. Much of this machinery appears functional, despite the unclear source of power sustaining it.'''

'''Within these factories, workers associated with Cicerone can often be found. These workers consist of both Wanderers and [[Entity 9]] (Facelings), who appear to operate and maintain the machinery. Their behavior is typically organized and purposeful, suggesting a structured system of production within the zone. Wanderers are generally tolerated in this area, though interference with ongoing work is discouraged.'''

'''Various resources can be found within the Industrial Zone, including [[Object 1|Almond Water]], [[Object 6|Moth Jelly]], and [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]]. However, these items are considered property of Cicerone and are not freely available. Wanderers seeking to obtain these resources must engage in trade or negotiation with members of the group. Unauthorized attempts to take items have been reported to result in hostility or expulsion from the area.'''

'''Cicerone primarily uses this zone to manufacture and process a wide range of commonly used objects, which are then distributed or traded with other [[Groups]] throughout the Backrooms. The Industrial Zone therefore serves as a central hub of production and economic activity within Level 540.'''

'''Like most other zones in Level 540, the Industrial Zone is relatively stable. While minor anomalous phenomena may occasionally occur, such events are generally infrequent and do not significantly disrupt the overall functionality of the area. This relative stability, combined with the presence of resources and organized activity, makes the Industrial Zone one of the more predictable regions within the level.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

== '''Residential Zone''' ==
'''The Residential Zone is a region that appears less frequently than the Industrial Zone within Level 540.'''

{{Blurimage|caption=Residential Zone in Level 540|file=residential zone in Level 540.jpeg}}

'''Unlike the factory-dominated Industrial Zone, this area consists of buildings designed for human habitation and basic needs. Most structures contain essential living spaces, including at least one bedroom, a kitchen, and a bathroom. Some buildings may also include additional rooms such as storage spaces or small dining areas. Higher-ranking members of Cicerone, as well as officials from [[M.E.G.|M.E.G.]], are known to reside in significantly larger and more comfortable homes. These residences often feature expanded layouts, including living rooms, multiple bedrooms, and higher-quality furnishings.'''

'''The architectural style of the Residential Zone closely resembles working-class housing from the early 20th century. Rows of modest homes line the streets, constructed primarily from brick and wood, with simple yet functional designs. In contrast, residences belonging to high-ranking individuals are styled after bourgeois homes from the 1920s, featuring more elaborate structures, decorative elements, and improved interior conditions.'''

'''This zone is considered one of the most stable areas within Level 540. Reports of [[Phenomenon 14|Non-Euclidean]] structures are extremely rare, making navigation significantly easier compared to other zones. Due to this stability, the Residential Zone has become a primary location for organized settlements. It is home to the [[M.E.G.|M.E.G.]] Base "White Wings," as well as a train station that connects directly to [[The Metro]]. Several communal areas maintained by Cicerone can also be found here, providing shelter, rest areas, and limited resources for wanderers.'''

== '''The Warped Zone''' ==
'''The Warped Zone of Level 540 is a rare and highly unstable region that becomes slightly more common the further one travels from the center of the level.'''

{{Blurimage|file=Street in the Warped Zone.png|caption=A photograph of wanderers in the Warped Zone of Level 540}}

'''This zone features a chaotic mixture of both residential and industrial structures. However, unlike other areas, nearly all buildings in the Warped Zone are affected by [[Phenomenon 14]]. This results in distorted architecture, impossible layouts, and shifting spatial geometry, making navigation extremely difficult and often disorienting. Paths may loop unexpectedly, interiors may be larger than their exteriors suggest, and entire structures can appear to change when not directly observed.'''

'''Cicerone utilizes the Warped Zone for the production and processing of rarer and more anomalous items. These include uncommon varieties of [[Object 10|Backshrooms]], [[Object 15|Firesalt]], and other poorly understood materials such as [[Object 30]]. Due to the instability of the area, only experienced individuals are typically assigned to work here.'''

'''Several structures within this zone are reportedly owned by a group known as Excelsior. These buildings are restricted, and access is only granted to members of [[A.A.E.G.|A.A.E.G.]]. Wanderers are strongly advised not to attempt entry, particularly into residences occupied by [[Entity 9|Facelings]], as this may result in hostile encounters or forced removal.'''

'''The Warped Zone is the only area in Level 540 where significant instability is consistently present. Anomalies such as [[Phenomenon 14|Non-Euclidean Geometry]] occur frequently, and environmental irregularities, such as street lamps activating automatically at night without any visible power source, are commonly reported. It is also suspected that [[Phenomenon 35|Roth Syndrome]] progresses more rapidly within this zone, although this has not been definitively confirmed. As a precaution, Cicerone distributes increased quantities of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] and other sanity-restoring items to individuals operating or residing in this region.'''

'''Additionally, the Warped Zone is noted for having a faint rose-colored tint overlaying its otherwise monochromatic environment. While this visual anomaly does not appear to have any direct effect on a wanderer’s sanity, its origin and purpose remain unknown.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

=='''High Concentration Industrial Zone'''==
'''The High Concentration Industrial Zone is located near the center of Level 540 and is considered one of its most hazardous regions.'''

{{Blurimage|caption=A photograph of the High Concentration Industrial Zone, photographer is still alive.|file=Captura de tela 2026-02-25 161804.png}}

'''This zone is characterized by significantly larger factory complexes than those found in the standard Industrial Zone, along with much narrower and more confined streets. The buildings here appear heavily degraded, with widespread corrosion and structural damage believed to be caused by prolonged exposure to acidic precipitation. The entire area is enveloped in a dense, persistent fog generated by the extreme levels of pollution emitted by the surrounding factories. Visibility is often severely reduced, making navigation difficult and disorienting.'''

'''It is presumed that these factories are primarily inhabited or operated by [[Entity 9|Facelings]]. However, no confirmed exploration of the factory interiors has been documented, as the environmental conditions within the High Concentration Industrial Zone are considered too dangerous for safe entry.'''

'''Any form of rainfall within this zone transforms into highly corrosive acid rain due to the concentration of airborne pollutants. Direct exposure to this rain can cause chemical burns, material degradation, and progressive injury over time. Even brief contact may result in irritation, while prolonged exposure can lead to severe damage to skin and equipment.'''

'''Unlike other areas of Level 540, this zone is extremely dangerous and should be avoided whenever possible. The air itself is highly contaminated, and inhalation of the dense industrial smoke can result in a wide range of serious symptoms, including:'''

*'''Intense coughing'''

*'''Difficulty breathing'''

*'''Chest pain'''

*'''General body weakness'''

*'''Severe eye irritation'''

*'''Cognitive impairment (brain fog)'''

*'''Difficulty thinking clearly'''

*'''Progressive physical deterioration, potentially leading to death after prolonged exposure'''

'''Due to these extreme conditions, exploration of the High Concentration Industrial Zone is considered nearly impossible. Most wanderers who enter this area either perish or suffer long-term respiratory damage. Cicerone has made multiple attempts to stabilize or filter the air within this zone; however, all such efforts have resulted in casualties, and no meaningful progress has been achieved. As a result, the zone remains largely unexplored and highly restricted.'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="8">| Weather |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''Level 540 experiences a wide variety of weather patterns, which can vary in frequency and intensity depending on the specific zone. While some weather events are relatively harmless, others can pose significant risks to wanderers.'''

==Rain==

'''Rain is the most common weather condition in Level 540. It typically occurs approximately every 36 hours and lasts for around 6 hours at a time. The rain behaves similarly to standard rainfall in [[The Frontrooms]], with no immediately harmful properties. However, prolonged exposure may still cause discomfort, especially due to the level’s already cold and damp atmosphere. Rain is observed across most zones, though its intensity may vary slightly depending on location.'''

==Almond Rain==

'''Almond Rain is an uncommon weather phenomenon that occasionally replaces normal rainfall in Level 540. It typically occurs once every 13 days and lasts for a duration similar to regular rain.'''

'''During this event, [[Object 1|Almond Water]] falls from the sky instead of normal water. Despite its unusual nature, Almond Rain behaves physically like standard rain and can accumulate in small pools or be collected in containers. This makes it a highly valuable occurrence for wanderers.'''

'''Due to its usefulness, several [[Backrooms Colonists|Backrooms Colonists]] have attempted to establish settlements in Level 540 specifically to harvest and filter the falling [[Object 1|Almond Water]]. However, these efforts are often complicated by the level’s unpredictable conditions and environmental hazards.'''

==Acid Rain==

'''Acid Rain functions similarly to acid rain found in [[The Frontrooms]], possessing corrosive properties capable of damaging both structures and organic tissue. Direct exposure can result in irritation, burns, and gradual material degradation.'''

'''This type of rainfall is primarily limited to the High Concentration Industrial Zone and nearby areas, where pollution levels are significantly higher. Wanderers are strongly advised to seek immediate shelter if Acid Rain begins, as even brief exposure can be harmful.'''

==Thunderstorms==

'''Thunderstorms are a relatively rare but dangerous weather event in Level 540. They occasionally replace standard rainfall and typically last for extended periods of up to 16 hours. These storms occur irregularly, usually every 24 to 60 days.'''

'''During thunderstorms, heavy rainfall, strong winds, and frequent lightning strikes can be observed. Visibility may be significantly reduced, and navigation becomes more difficult.'''

'''There is also an extremely low chance that a natural disaster may occur during these storms. The most notable recorded event was a tornado in 1912, which caused significant damage to parts of the Industrial Zone. It was rated F4 on the Fujita scale. While such events are rare, their potential severity makes thunderstorms one of the more dangerous weather conditions in Level 540.'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="8">| Entities |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

==[[Entity 9|'''Facelings''']]==
{{Entity Class|Agg=1|Int=3|Dan=2|no=9|Hab= they inhabit most levels.|}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''[[Entity 9|Facelings]] are common entities found throughout the factories of Level 540.'''

'''Within this level, [[Entity 9|Facelings]] primarily function as workers under Cicerone, acting as organized and efficient employees rather than hostile entities. They are frequently observed operating machinery, transporting materials, and maintaining production lines within the Industrial Zones. Their behavior appears structured and coordinated, suggesting a form of hierarchy or command system.'''

'''Wanderers are strongly advised not to interfere with their work. While Facelings are typically neutral, they may become agitated if disrupted, especially in active factory environments. In such cases, they may attempt to remove the source of interference, either by forcing wanderers to leave or, in rare instances, acting with hostility. Maintaining distance and avoiding direct interaction is generally the safest approach when encountering them.'''
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

==[[Entity 3|'''Smilers''']]==
{{Entity Class|Agg=5|Int=5|Dan=5|no=3|Hab=Dark areas of any level}}
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
'''[[Entity 3|Smilers]] are common sights during the nighttime within Level 540.'''

'''These entities are typically found lurking in darker areas of the level, taking advantage of the reduced visibility after sunset. However, Smilers consistently avoid well-lit environments, particularly areas illuminated by the street lamps scattered throughout the city. This behavior makes the lighting system of Level 540 an important natural defense for wanderers.'''

'''Traveling along streets with a high concentration of functioning lamps significantly reduces the risk of encountering or being attacked by Smilers. In most cases, remaining within illuminated areas is sufficient to deter them entirely. Conversely, straying into poorly lit alleys, abandoned buildings, or areas where lamps are non-functional greatly increases the likelihood of an encounter.'''

'''Wanderers are strongly advised to plan their movements around available light sources during the night and to avoid unnecessary travel through darkened sections of the level. Carrying additional light sources can further improve safety, although the effectiveness of artificial light compared to the level’s lamps may vary. Staying within lit paths remains the most reliable method of avoiding Smiler-related threats.'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><font size="8">| Colonies & Outposts |</font></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

=='''[[M.E.G.|M.E.G.]] Base "White Wings"'''==

{{Blurimage|file=Captura de tela 2026-02-18 180108.png|caption=M.E.G Base "White Wings" in Level 540.}}

*'''Located within the Residential Zone of Level 540.'''

*'''Maintains direct trade relations with Cicerone.'''

*'''Provides shelter, guidance, and essential resources to newly arrived wanderers.'''

*'''Currently staffed by approximately 10 permanent members and 50 rotating personnel.'''

*'''Open to trade and cooperative interactions with other groups and individuals.'''

=='''Cicerone'''==

*'''A massive and highly organized colony, currently consisting of approximately 3,106 members, with numbers steadily increasing.'''

*'''Willing to trade a wide range of manufactured goods in exchange for machinery and other useful resources.'''

*'''Actively accepts new members, provided they are willing to contribute through labor within the Industrial Zones.'''

*'''Exports large quantities of factory-produced items to groups such as [[M.E.G.|M.E.G.]], [[Architect Industries]], and the [[Backroom Colonists|Backrooms Colonists]].'''

*'''Maintains a workforce largely composed of [[Entity 9|Facelings]], who function as employees within their production system.'''

*'''Currently led by Chairman Raymon 9.'''

*'''Operates under a structured, production-focused system with strong industrial and economic priorities.'''

*'''No confirmed rivalries, though internal tensions with certain groups have been speculated.'''

=='''Excelsior'''==

*'''Located within the Warped Zone of Level 540.'''

*'''Composed of approximately 35 [[Entity 9|Facelings]].'''

*'''Generally hostile toward Cicerone and its human workforce, for reasons that remain unclear.'''

*'''Maintains neutral to friendly relations with [[M.E.G.|M.E.G.]] and several other groups.'''

*'''Engages in selective trade, primarily for items of specific interest.'''

*'''Allied with the [[A.A.E.G.|A.A.E.G.]].'''

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}

=='''Entrances and Exits'''==

==='''Entrances'''===

* '''Finding an old watch on any level will lead here. '''
* '''Entering a factory in [[Level 11]] has a small chance of entering here.'''
==='''Exits'''===

* '''Opening a book titled ''"The Party Is Already Dead"'' will lead to [[Level 827]].'''
* '''Entering a black concrete room may lead one to [[Level 442]].''' (Not recommended)
* '''Entering a café has a chance of leading to [[Level 610]].'''
